Milwaukee rookie point guard T.J. Ford was taken off the court on a stretcher after falling hard during the
fourth quarter of the Bucks' game against Minnesota on Tuesday night.
related.linkText: Bucks rookie Ford suffers sprained neck
related.title: Guard says he briefly lost feeling in extremities
related.headline: Guard says he briefly lost feeling in extremities

article.headline: Cassell free throws seal it for Minnesota
article.linkText: Bucks' Ford injures neck in loss to Wolves
article.story:
MILWAUKEE (AP) -- Sam Cassell couldn't keep his emotions in check. He scored 29 points in his return to Milwaukee and calmly sank six free throws in the closing seconds of Minnesota's 108-102 victory over the Bucks on Tuesday night. But Cassell got emotional twice. First, he drew a technical foul for arguing two offensive fouls. Then, he watched Bucks rookie T.J. Ford get taken off the court on a stretcher after falling to the floor and laying motionless in the fourth quarter. Ford was taken to St. Luke's Medical Center, where X-rays revealed a sprained neck. He was admitted to the hospital overnight and didn't make the team's trip to Boston for a game Wednesday night. Ford told teammates while he lay motionless on the floor that he had no feeling in his extremities, fellow point guard Damon Jones said. Jones said team medical personnel later told the players that Ford had regained feeling in his extremities as he was being carried off the court to an ambulance. "I was scared until I found out he had some movement in his legs," Cassell said. "T.J. is a personal friend of mine. We're all out of the Houston area and I got to know T.J. a lot this summer. He's a real good kid. He's going to be a real good point guard a lot of years in the league. "Once he went down, I told him, 'Come on, man. Fight, you have to fight!" Cassell also drew back-to-back offensive foul calls and then a technical while continuing to argue on the bench. Other than that, Cassell was calm and cool in his first trip back to the Bradley Center since being traded to Minnesota last summer. "He's been having big games almost every night," Timberwolves coach Flip Saunders said. "I don't think he was overemotional like he's been in some games. He got emotional about a couple of fouls they called, but I thought he was very workmanlike down the stretch." Cassell, who played 4{ seasons with the Bucks before being traded to Minnesota along with Ervin Johnson for Joe Smith last summer, sealed the Wolves' 10th straight win over Milwaukee by sinking all six of his foul shots in the final 19 seconds. He hit two foul shots after Michael Redd's 3-pointer made it 101-97, and he sank two more after Keith Van Horn's 3 pulled Milwaukee to 103-100 with 16 seconds left. Cassell's two foul shots with 9 seconds left iced the win, which made Minnesota the first NBA team to reach 20 road wins this season. Latrell Sprewell, a Milwaukee native, added 23 points, and Kevin Garnett had his NBA-leading 51st double-double with 16 points and 18 rebounds. He tied his own club record with his 19th consecutive double-double. "I like the gym, I guess," Sprewell said. "I always circle the Milwaukee games here. I play in front of my family and I have a lot of family here. It's always special." Redd and Van Horn each scored 25 for Milwaukee. The Timberwolves, who are 20-9 away from Target Center, led 57-47 at halftime and were never threatened until the final minute. Minnesota, which has won eight straight at the Bradley Center since last losing in Milwaukee on Feb. 8, 1995, closed the third quarter on a 12-2 run to take an 86-65 lead into the fourth quarter. Cassell lost his cool in the third quarter. He was whistled for back-to-back offensive fouls and took a seat with 8:27 left. He drew a technical 16 seconds later when he yelled at official Scott Foster from the bench. But Redd's foul shot only pulled Milwaukee to 66-54. Later, Cassell playfully gestured at official Jim Clark, who called the charges, during a timeout. Ford fell hard after scoring and getting fouled by Mark Madsen on a drive to the basket with 4:34 left. "I heard the impact on the floor and from that point on I just started praying for him," Jones said. It appeared as though Ford fell on his tailbone or a hip, possibly jarring his neck. He rolled onto his side, grimacing in pain. "I hate to see anybody carried off on a stretcher, let alone one of my teammates. It was a scary situation," Smith said. "I was right there and saw him come down. It's tough to see somebody carried off like that."

Game notes
Desmond Mason's first-quarter dunk was disqualified because he hung on the rim as the ball rattled around the cylinder for basket interference. ... Saunders is 13-3 against Milwaukee.
